<item>
            <title>[LU-12143] sanity-lfsck: test_27b	</title>
                <link>https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-12143</link>
                <project id="10000" key="LU">Lustre</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;This issue was created by maloo for paf &amp;lt;pfarrell@whamcloud.com&amp;gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This issue relates to the following test suite run: &lt;a href=&quot;https://testing.whamcloud.com/test_sets/1c630072-5357-11e9-92fe-52540065bddc&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://testing.whamcloud.com/test_sets/1c630072-5357-11e9-92fe-52540065bddc&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Error: &apos;Timeout occurred after 252 mins, last suite running was sanity-lfsck, restarting cluster to continue tests&apos; &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;== sanity-lfsck test 27b: LFSCK can recreate the lost remote parent directory as orphan ============== 22:33:21 (1553985201)&lt;br/&gt;
#####&lt;br/&gt;
The remote parent referenced by the MDT-object linkEA is lost.&lt;br/&gt;
The namespace LFSCK will re-create the lost parent as orphan.&lt;br/&gt;
#####&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;0x2400032e2:0xb:0x0&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
Inject failure stub on MDT0 to simulate the case that&lt;br/&gt;
foo&apos;s name entry will be removed, but the foo&apos;s object&lt;br/&gt;
and its linkEA are kept in the system. And then remove&lt;br/&gt;
the parent directory.&lt;br/&gt;
CMD: onyx-42vm9 /usr/sbin/lctl set_param fail_loc=0x1624&lt;br/&gt;
fail_loc=0x1624&lt;br/&gt;
CMD: onyx-42vm9 /usr/sbin/lctl set_param fail_loc=0&lt;br/&gt;
fail_loc=0&lt;br/&gt;
Trigger namespace LFSCK to repair the missing remote name entry&lt;br/&gt;
CMD: onyx-42vm9 /usr/sbin/lctl lfsck_start -M lustre-MDT0000 -t namespace -r -A&lt;br/&gt;
Started LFSCK on the device lustre-MDT0000: scrub namespace&lt;br/&gt;
CMD: onyx-42vm9 /usr/sbin/lctl lfsck_query -t namespace -M lustre-MDT0000 -w |&lt;br/&gt;
		      awk &apos;/^namespace_mdts_completed/ &lt;/p&gt;
{ print \$2 }
&lt;p&gt;&apos;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
